                            <p class="text-justify">When you're planning a trip, you normally seek advice from your friends on how to save money on airfare. If it doesn't work, you'll have to look it up on the internet. It's not like there's anything to lose by doing so. However, did you know that there are a lot of misconceptions about cheap flight booking? It would help if you were mindful that not all information available on the internet is accurate. As a result, we've come up with a plan to educate you on some essential facts. We understand that you want to receive the most outstanding value possible when flying. So, we'll ensure that you don't miss out on any opportunities and that you fly high without being misled. Before we begin, it's important to note that this information applies to <b>domestic and international online ticket bookings</b>. So, let's get this started right away: </p>

                            <h2>Always search on private/incognito mode</h2>
                            <p class="text-justify">This myth is the worst one. Why should airlines be any different? Many organizations around the world use cookies to track and understand their consumers' internet habits. It makes perfect sense for them to do so since they can identify the flights you've been looking at and then raise the prices of those routes to make more money. To avoid this, it's generally recommended that you use incognito mode on your browser. However, the fact is that booking businesses have conducted numerous researches, and there is no evidence to imply that airlines behave in this manner. According to the studies, there is no price difference between using incognito mode and using your search engine properly. Although, seat prices are continuously changing as quickly as by the minute which is why you'll see costs fluctuating. </p>

                            <h3>The truth behind the 'Best Booking Website' </h3>

                            <p class="text-justify">Absolutely myth, there is no best booking website out there, remember that. Every website has its own set of rules and price charts. Many people believe that purchasing from a 3rd party website will give you additional discounts and promo codes compared to the airline's official website. This is, however, true as 3rd party websites usually buy airline seats on a bulk basis. Nevertheless, keep in mind that these websites too can change prices depending on demand and supply. So when you see some of the best deals, grab it right away because you never know the cost of those tickets after some time. It's crucial to understand that platform prices differ. As a result, rather than relying on a single booking website or meta-search engine, it is recommended that you examine several booking websites and meta-search engines before making your decision. </p>

                            <h3>Round-Trip ticket bookings are usually cheaper</h3>

                            <p class="text-justify">This is another myth. The majority of the sources will advise you to book your return flight ticket when you are making a reservation. Buying a round-trip ticket instead of two one-way tickets, either on the same airline or by combining flights on different airlines, has long been thought to save money. In today's time, there are many websites through which you can avail money-saving <a href="https://www.faresmatch.com/one-way-flights-deals.aspx">one-way flights</a> for yourself. You can also look for two one-way tickets instead to get the cheap fares combination for flight tickets. </p>

                            <h3>Perfect time for Flight Booking</h3>

                            <p class="text-justify">You've probably heard that there's a certain day before your vacation when you should <b>book your flight to get the best deal</b>. The truth, on the other hand, is that airfares do not fluctuate that much. According to research, if you book your travel 21 days ahead of time and make sure there isn't a prominent event taking place at your holiday destination, airfare stays pretty much the same every day, with a $50 difference here and there. This isn't to say that prices can't shift dramatically because of algorithms and other factors, but it's unlikely, and there isn't a set of rules for the same, making no time to consider the perfect time. </p>

                            <h3>Grab best offers on Last-minute Fares</h3>

                            <p class="text-justify">No, this is not the truth. Years back, airlines used to give fantastic <b>offers on last-minute flights</b>. However, they now understand shoppers’ demands. They have adept at cutting capacity, which means airlines now routinely fill up their seats, making no way for passengers to get last-minute discounts. So make sure to make your reservation at least seven days in advance for low-cost carriers and four weeks on other airlines. Note that booking flights at the last moment can also make you pay the same amount as business travelers. In short, there is no chance of getting the deal mentioned above. </p>

                            <h3>Tuesday is the cheapest day to book</h3>

                            <p class="text-justify">Travel Tuesday, this well-kept secret for finding a great airfare, has even been given its name. This myth evolved from a grain of truth, specifically the once-common practice of airlines "loading" their tickets into their reservation computers on Mondays, meaning that there would be more <a href="https://www.faresmatch.com/deals-under-99.aspx">low-cost flights</a> available the following day. Instead of giving the best rates on a specific day of the week, airlines are increasingly turning to flash sales to boost business, which can occur at any time. So no, Tuesday isn't the cheapest day to book. </p>

                            <h3>Low-cost carriers will always be cheaper than the major carriers</h3>

                            <p class="text-justify">A few years ago, there were two sorts of airlines: higher-priced scheduled carriers and low-cost charter firms. After the government deregulated airlines 40 years ago, that distinction vanished, and now it appears like every airline is attempting to be everything to everyone. While you'd think that an airline with reduced costs would be able to pass those savings on to customers, much like a bargain warehouse could offer the same things for cheaper than a high-end store, that isn't necessarily the case. Even though big carriers such as <a href="https://www.faresmatch.com/delta-airlines-flights-reservations.aspx">Delta Airlines</a> have higher unit costs than Allegiant Airlines, new pricing classes such as Basic Economic have blurred the lines. </p>

                            <h3>Connecting Flights are less expensive than a Non-stop one</h3>

                            <p class="text-justify">When it comes to airline flights, a nonstop flight is usually preferable to one that takes you to your destination through an out-of-the-way stop, which adds hours to your journey. On the other hand, if you take a connecting flight, you have to get down at an airport to take another flight after that, which many sources believe to be cheaper than the first option. However, it is not the absolute truth as many times, when you take connecting flights, you may end up paying more cost than the nonstop one. So consider your decision, do the entire math, and only <a href="https://www.faresmatch.com/flights.aspx">book the most reasonable flight</a>.</p>

                            <h2 class="text-justify">Conclusion: </h2>

